General Release Mitigation



-Automatic and remotely operated shut-offs to limit release quantities;

-Strategically located valves to isolate leaks;

-Hydrocarbon detectors at key areas to warn of a chemical release and initiate a terminal shutdown;

-Deluge system installed in offload area; and

-Fire water monitors installed near butane storage vessel.



General Emergency Response



-Emergency alert system;

-Periodic emergency training for employees;

-Communication systems with local emergency responders and regulatory agencies;

-Emergency drills with plant personnel, regulatory agencies, and community emergency responders to enhance response skills and coordination among agencies;

-Mutual Aid with local Fire Departments; and

-Participation with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) or its equivalent.



Further, the Lansing LP Terminal complies with the National Fire Protection Association's (NFPA's) Liquefied Petroleum Gas (LPG) Code (NFPA-58) requirements for LP Gas storage. In addition to the presence of appropriate controls to prevent and limit possible releases of butane, if a release does occur, a Facility Response Plan (FRP) is in place for the Facility and response activities are coordinated with the Looking Glass Regional Fire Authority and Clinton County LEPC.



C. FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY



The Lansing LP Terminal has an excellent record of accident prevention. The terminal keeps records for all significant accidental chemical releases that occur at our facility. This is a "new" butane blending process; consequently, there have been no accidents within the past five (5) years resulting from the chemical release of materials covered under the EPA RMP regulation.



